      "intro": "If your loved one is 60+ and on a fixed income, they may qualify for monthly food assistance through SNAP's simplified enrollment programs. New York offers two streamlined options: ESAP (for senior/disabled households with no earned income) and NYSCAP (for SSI recipients living alone). These programs feature simpler applications and a 36-month certification period.\n\nThe benefit amount is based on household size and net income, loaded monthly onto an EBT card. Because these programs use data matching with Social Security, your loved one won't need to provide as much documentation or attend frequent recertification interviews; however, they will still need to complete a non-mandatory interim report at the 18-month midpoint to keep benefits active.\n\nEven if your loved one's income seems too high for standard SNAP, New York has expanded eligibility for seniors and disabled adults. Households where all members are 60+ or disabled can have a gross monthly income up to $2,608 for a single person to qualify.",
