      "intro": "If your loved one is 65 or older and owns their home in New York City, the Senior Citizen Homeowners' Exemption (SCHE) could reduce their property taxes by 5% to 50% based on income.\n\nThe amount of the reduction depends on total combined household income. Currently, those with a combined income of $50,000 or less may qualify for the maximum 50% reduction. For those earning above $50,000, the exemption percentage decreases on a sliding scale, with eligibility for a 5% reduction extending up to a combined income of $58,399.\n\nBecause this exemption reduces the property's assessed value, your loved one's property tax bill drops directly. For example, if their home is assessed at $400,000 and they qualify for the 50% reduction, they would only pay taxes on $200,000 of assessed value. The program covers one-, two-, or three-family homes, condominiums, and cooperative apartments across all five NYC boroughs.\n\nTo qualify, your loved one must have owned and lived in the property as their primary residence for at least 12 consecutive months before applying. Total combined household income includes most sources, such as Social Security, pensions, retirement benefits, interest, dividends, and other earnings.",
